DB wraps the database connection and info.

``/DB type:
type DB struct {
  db *sql.DB
  info Info
}
``

import the main db package and various drivers.

``/import:
"database/sql"
_ "github.com/mattn/go-sqlite3"
_ "github.com/microsoft/go-mssqldb"
``

Info holds the connection info for a db target.

``/Info type:
type Info struct {
  Target string
  Type string      `yaml:"type"`
  Database string  `yaml:"database"`
  User string  `yaml:"user"`
  Password string  `yaml:"password"`
  Host string    `yaml:"host"`
  Port int      `yaml:"port"`
}
``

Conf is a map of Infos keyed by string.

``/Conf type:
type Conf map[string]Info
``

Open opens a db connection to the requested target from .dbc file.

``/Open:
func Open(target string) (*DB, error) { 
  ``.``
}
``

make a new db instance.

``
  db := new(DB)
``

get the connection info for target.

``
  var err error
  db.info, err = info(target)
  if err != nil { return nil, err }
``

open the db.

``
  db.db, err = sql.Open(db.info.Type, connstr(db.info))
  if err != nil { return nil, err }
  return db, nil
``

Close closes a dbcq connection.

``/Close:
func (d *DB) Close() {
  d.db.Close()
}
``

Qfad (query-fetch-all-dict) queries and returns the result as a slice
of maps keyed by column name.  the keys are lower case.

``/Qfad:
func (d *DB) Qfad(query string/*, args ...string*/) ([]map[string]interface{}, error) {
  ``.``
}
``

code adapted from https://stackoverflow.com/q/30569005

send the query to db, get the result rows.

``
  rows, err := d.db.Query(query) //, args)
  //defer rows.Close()
  if err != nil { return nil, err }
``

get the column names.

``
  colnames, err := rows.Columns()
  if err != nil { return nil, err }
``

make a cols slice for the scanned values. the scanner takes pointers, so point to each place in the cols slice. 

``
  cols := make([]interface{}, len(colnames))
  colptrs := make([]interface{}, len(colnames))
  for i := 0; i < len(colnames); i++ {
    colptrs[i] = &cols[i]
  }
``

go over the rows and put each row into a map keyed by column name.

``
  out := make([]map[string]interface{}, 0)
  for rows.Next() {
    ``.``
  }
``

scan into the cols slice using colptrs (that points to cols).

``
    err = rows.Scan(colptrs...)
    if err != nil { return nil, err }
``

make a map and put in the values. this works cause the column order is the same for Columns() and Scan(). 

``
    mymap := make(map[string]interface{})
    
    for i, val := range cols {
      mymap[strings.ToLower(colnames[i])] = val
    }
``

variable sized numbers like numeric(19, 0), seem to be returned as uint8 (byte) slices.

convert them to ints by going via strings, as suggested here: https://www.bacancytechnology.com/qanda/golang/how-to-convert-from-byte-to-int-in-go

see also the getInt() function at the end.

``
    for k, val := range mymap {
      switch val.(type) {
      case []uint8:
        s := string(val.([]byte))
        num, err := strconv.Atoi(s)
        if err != nil { return nil, err }
        mymap[k] = num
      }
    }
``

append the map to the slice.

``
    out = append(out, mymap)
``

after the loop, return.

``../
  rows.Close()
  return out, nil
``

